      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA25-kiḷavi">itu talaimakaḷait tōḻi kuṟai nayappak kūṟiyatu.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante told HER to grant [HIS] request.</p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA25">
<l>            avvaḷai verini ṉarakkīrt taṉṉa</l>
<l>            cevvari yitaḻa cēṇāṟu piṭavi</l>
<l>            ṉaṟuntā tāṭiya tumpi pacuṅkēḻp</l>
<l>            poṉṉuraik kalli ṉaṉṉiṟam peṟūum</l>
<l>            vaḷamalai nāṭa ṉeruna ṉammoṭu </l>
<l>            kiḷaimali ciṟutiṉaik kiḷikaṭin tacaiic</l>
<l>            colliṭam peṟāaṉ peyarntaṉaṉ peyarnta</l>
<l>            talla laṉṟatu kātalan tōḻi</l>
<l>            tātuṇ vēṭkaiyiṟ pōtuterin tūtā</l>
<l>            vaṇṭō raṉṉavavaṉ ṟaṇṭāk kāṭci </l>
<l>            kaṇṭuṅ kaḻaṟoṭi valittaveṉ</l>
<l>            paṇpil ceyti niṉaippā kiṉṟē.</l>
        </lg>
        <lg xml:lang="en">

<l>The man from the fertile mountain,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the bee that played in the fragrant pollen of the</l>
<l rend="indent2">Piṭavu, that is fragrant [even] at a distance, with red-lined petals,</l>
<l rend="indent3">as if drawn with vermilion on the back of a pretty conch,<note place="foot">An alternative understanding of this line is pointed out by Th.A., namely: "as if drawn with purple [won] from the back of that shell" − which would be a reference to red colour won from the purple snail.</note></l>
<l rend="indent">takes the good colour of a stone rubbed with fresh brilliant gold<note place="foot">For the animal golden from pollen and compared to a touch-stone cf. KT 192.4.</note>,</l>
<l>after staying [and] chasing away with us yesterday</l>
<l rend="indent3">the parakeets from the little millet, coming in flocks<note place="foot">By position one would rather expect <term xml:lang="ta">kiḷai mali</term> to be an attribute to <term xml:lang="ta">tiṉai</term> (i.e. "in dense groups"), but <term xml:lang="ta">kiḷai</term> usually is said of groups of animals, and so it seems preferable to take it with the <term xml:lang="ta">kiḷi-s</term>.</note>,</l>
<l>he returned without getting an opportunity to speak.</l>
<l>[His] returning is no misfortune, it [is] love, [my] pretty<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kātal-am</term>: perhaps the best way to make sense of am here is to take it as an adjective. More natural would be <term xml:lang="ta">kātalam</term> as an attribute to <term xml:lang="ta">tōḻi</term>, but atu makes clear that we have to split and read a second sentence.</note> friend.</l>
<l>The thought of my doing something unnatural has come up,</l>
<l rend="indent3">induced by [the one with] anklets and bracelets,<note place="foot">Here <term xml:lang="ta">kaḻal-toṭi</term> probably should be taken as a metonym for <term xml:lang="ta">Murukaṉ</term> (which might also mean "the one with loosening bracelets"; cf. KT 1), the point being that SHE wonders whether <term xml:lang="ta">Murukaṉ</term> endowed her with some sort of bewitching power.</note></l>
<l rend="indent">just when<note place="foot">Why <term xml:lang="ta">kaṇṭum</term> here? The usual concessive function of absolutive with -um does not fit here. Can it refer to a certain point of time, "even when" or "just when", or even the ‘modern’ "as soon as"?</note> he had an unobstructed sight [of me], just like a bee</l>
<l rend="indent2">not filled up after searching a bud in [its] desire to eat pollen.</l>
        </lg>
